04657nam a22006135i 9789633863688DE-B159720221107062033.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221107t20212021hu     fo  d z      eng d  a2020036441  a9789633863688  a(DE-B1597)633597  a(OCoLC)1338019783  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahucHU00aHQ1719b.G56 2021 4aHQ1719b.G56 2021 7aHIS0100102bisacsh04a305.48/697094972231 aGiomi, Fabio, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMaking Muslim Women European :bVoluntary Associations, Gender, and Islam in Post-Ottoman Bosnia and Yugoslavia (1878-1941) /cFabio Giomi. 1aBudapest ;aNew York : bCentral European University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (410 p.) :b40 photographs, 5 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCEU Press Studies in the History of Medicine00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tLISTS OF ABBREVIATIONS -- tLISTS OF FIGURES -- tLISTS OF TABLES -- tACKNOWLEDGEMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- tCHAPTER 1 AT THE MARGINS OF THE HABSBURG CIVILIZING MISSION -- tCHAPTER 2 DOMESTICATING THE MUSLIM WOMAN QUESTION -- tCHAPTER 3 MUSLIM, FEMALE AND VOLUNTEER -- tCHAPTER 4 CALLING FOR CHANGE -- tCHAPTER 5 PUTTING CHANGE INTO PRACTICE -- tCHAPTER 6 A TASTE FOR CELEBRATION -- tCHAPTER 7 UNFORESEEN CONSEQUENCES -- tCONCLUSIONS -- tCONSULTED ARCHIVES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThis social, cultural, and political history of Slavic Muslim women of the Yugoslav region in the first decades of the post-Ottoman era is the first to provide a comprehensive overview of the issues confronting these women. It is based on a study of voluntary associations (philanthropic, cultural, Islamic-traditionalist, and feminist) of the period. It is broadly held that Muslim women were silent and relegated to a purely private space until 1945, when the communist state "unveiled" and "liberated" them from the top down. After systematic archival research in Bosnia, Croatia, Serbia, and Austria, Fabio Giomi challenges this view by showing: • How different sectors of the Yugoslav elite through association publications, imagined the role of Muslim women in post-Ottoman times, and how Muslim women took part in the construction or the contestation of these narratives. • How associa­tions employed different means in order to forge a generation of "New Muslim Women" able to cope with the post-Ottoman political and social circumstances. • And how Muslim women used the tools provided by the associations in order to pursue their own projects, aims and agendas. The insights are relevant for today's challenges facing Muslim women in Europe. The text is illustrated with exceptional photographs.  afunded by Knowledge Unlatched  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aMuslim womenzBosnia and HerzegovinaxSocial conditions. 0aMuslim womenzYugoslaviaxSocial conditions. 0aWomenzBosnia and HerzegovinaxSocieties and clubsxHistory. 0aWomenzEuropexSocial conditions. 0aWomenzYugoslaviaxSocieties and clubsxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Eastern.2bisacsh  a20th century, Bosnia, Islam, Religion, Social history, Women, Yugoslavia.2 aKnowledge Unlatchedefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2021z978311078049940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789633863688zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789633863688/original  a978-3-11-078049-9 Central European University Press eBook-Pa